stylometry: A simulation model imitates a real life situation, including uncertainties. It shows a distribution of results, rather than just one single result. This is imperative because it shows comparisons.  Simulation models are good when answering what if questions, and allow results to be shown without having to build a physical model.  An example of simulation would be if a company was attempting to create a new model car, and wanted to know the profit they would make in 10 years.  They could run a simulation model because of all of the uncertainties- demand, cost to product.  It could then show the distribution of results, in order to help the company view the possible outcomes.
